Cdl and ECSA are appraised from cyclic voltammetry (Fig. 9
                     ). Cyclic voltammetry for scan rates 20 mV/s, 40 mV/s, 60 mV/s, 80 mV/s, 100 mV/s and 120 mV/s are taken. The existence of non-Faradaic current is visible from the rectangular shape of CV [81]. It confirms the nature of capacitance as double layer capacitance rather than pseudo capacitance [81]. Non-Faradaic current denotes that the ion exchange process between the electrolyte and electrode is absent in the electrocatalysis. From Fig. 9, values of current densities for various scan rates at a given overpotential can be estimated. The slope of the graph drawn between current densities and scan rates gives the value of Cdl. Maximum values of Cdl and ECSA are obtained for MoS2−x 220 (23.8 mF/cm2, 595/cm2). MoS2−x 140 have obtained minimum Cdl and ECSA (13 mF/cm2, 325/cm2). Since the value of Cdl indicates the number of charges of the catalysts that actively participate in catalytic activity, electrolysis prefers catalysts with greater Cdl and ECSA. Cyclic voltammetry parameters are listed in Table 2
                     .
